Question Text: You have noticed that a server with IP 145.45.3.2 doesn’t respond to requests. What command will you type first in order to test connectivity between your device and the server?
LLM Explanation: The 'ping' command is the correct choice to test connectivity between your device and the server with IP address 145.45.3.2. Ping uses ICMP echo request and echo reply messages to determine if a host is reachable and responsive on an IP network. The other options - 'request', 'check', and the duplicate 'ping' - are not valid commands for testing network connectivity.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: IP Services', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ios-nx-os-software/ios-software-releases-121-mainline/12778-ping-traceroute.html']

protocol is down

Question Text: Which of the following commands lists detailed information about the route 156.10.2.0.
Choices:
a. show route 156.10.2.0
b. show routing table 156.10.2.0
c. show ip route 156.10.2.0
d. show route table 156.10.2.0
LLM Explanation: The 'show ip route' command is used to display the IP routing table on Cisco routers and switches. By specifying the IP address or network after the command, it will display detailed information about the specific route, including the outgoing interface, next hop IP address, administrative distance, and metric. The other options listed are not valid Cisco IOS commands for displaying routing information.

Question Text:
You are connected on a router R1, Which command will you type the command to connect to R2 using SSH. Login credentials in order to get access to R2. R2’s IP address: 145.167.2.1
username: userexamsdigest
password: passexamsdigest
Choices:
a. ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.1
passexamsdigest
b. ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.2
passexamsdigest
c. ssh -l userexams 145.167.2.1
passexamsdigest
d. ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.1
examsdigest
LLM Explanation: To connect to R2 using SSH from R1, the correct command is 'ssh -l userexamsdigest 145.167.2.1' followed by entering the password 'passexamsdigest' when prompted. This uses the provided IP address of R2 (145.167.2.1) and the given username (userexamsdigest). The other options have incorrect IP addresses, usernames, or passwords.

Question Text: After configuring a working router interface with IP address/mask 10.1.1.100/26, which of the following routes would you expect to see in the output of the show ip route command? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. A connected route for subnet 10.1.1.64 255.255.255.192
b. A local route for host 10.1.1.64 255.255.255.255
c. A local route for host 10.1.1.100 255.255.255.255
d. A local route for host 10.1.1.100 255.255.255.192
e. A connected route for subnet 10.1.1.0 255.255.255.0
LLM Explanation: With an IP address of 10.1.1.100/26, the subnet is 10.1.1.64/26 (255.255.255.192). This will create a connected route for the subnet 10.1.1.64/26 in the routing table. Additionally, a local route will be created for the specific IP address 10.1.1.100/32 (255.255.255.255) assigned to the interface.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: IP Routing Essentials', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: You are responsible to configure a static route for the network 156.187.45.0/24 using the IP address 156.187.80.45 as the next-hop IP. Which command will you type to meet the requirement?
LLM Explanation: The correct command to configure a static route for the network 156.187.45.0/24 using the IP address 156.187.80.45 as the next-hop is: 'ip route 156.187.45.0 255.255.255.0 156.187.80.45'. This command specifies the destination network (156.187.45.0), the subnet mask (255.255.255.0 which corresponds to /24), and the next-hop IP address (156.187.80.45). The other options have incorrect subnet masks or next-hop IP addresses.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: IP Routing', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/16448-default.html']

Question Text: Which of the following options are things that a standard IP ACL could be configured to do? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. Match the exact source IP address
b. Match all IP addresses in a subnet with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
c. Match IP addresses 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
d. Match only the packet’s destination IP address
LLM Explanation: A standard IP ACL can match the exact source IP address and only the packet's destination IP address. It cannot match a range of addresses or a subnet without including other addresses.

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #1: Permit packets from 186.33.2.3
ACL command #1: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3
b. access-list 1 deny 186.33.2.3
c. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.0
d. access-list 1 deny 186.33.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3'. This command creates a standard ACL with the number 1 and permits packets specifically from the IP address 186.33.2.3. The other options are incorrect because they either use 'deny' instead of 'permit' or specify a different IP address or network that does not match the given criteria.

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #2: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets
ACL command #2: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 1 permit 57.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 deny 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a'. The access-list command 'access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255' matches the criteria to permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets. The wildcard mask '0.0.0.255' allows any value in the last octet, effectively matching all hosts with 56.57.2 in the first three octets.

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #3: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets
ACL command #3: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255
b. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.255.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.58.0.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: To permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets, the correct wildcard mask should be 0.0.255.255. This mask allows any value in the last two octets while fixing the first two octets as 56.57. Option 'a' uses 0.255.255.255 which is not the correct wildcard mask. Option 'c' has an incorrect wildcard mask and also specifies the wrong IP address (56.58 instead of 56.57). Option 'd' uses a wildcard mask of 0.0.0.0 which would only match the exact IP 56.57.0.0, not all IPs starting with 56.57.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: ACLs and WAN Technologies', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #4: Permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5, sent to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24
ACL command #4: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq 23
b. access-list 101 permit any any
c. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
d. access-list 101 deny tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
LLM Explanation: The correct ACL command to permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5 to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24 is 'access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www'. This command allows TCP traffic from the specific host 65.5.5.5 to any host in the 65.5.6.0/24 subnet, but only if the destination port is 'www' (port 80), which is used for web traffic.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #5: Permit any and every IPv4 packet
ACL command #5: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit ip any any
b. access-list 101 deny ip any any
c. access-list 101 permit ip 0.0.0.0 any
d. access-list 101 permit ip any 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a. access-list 101 permit ip any any'. This ACL command permits any and every IPv4 packet, as specified in the criteria. The 'any' keyword in both the source and destination fields of the ACL matches any IP address, effectively allowing all IPv4 traffic.

Question Text: Type the access-list command that permits all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24. Use the ACL number 50 for the ACL rule.
Choices:
a. access-list 50 permit 14.15.17.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 50 deny 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.255.255.255
d. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit all packets from the 14.15.16.0/24 subnet is 'access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255'. The ACL number is specified as 50. The subnet 14.15.16.0 is used with a wildcard mask of 0.0.0.255, which matches any host within that /24 subnet range.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Given the following access-list command access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255, choose the exact range of IP addresses, matched by the command.
LLM Explanation: The access-list command 'access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255' matches the IP address range 192.168.4.0 - 192.168.4.255. The first part '192.168.4.0' specifies the network address, and the second part '0.0.0.255' is the wildcard mask. A wildcard mask of '0.0.0.255' means that the last octet can vary from 0 to 255, while the first three octets must match exactly. Therefore, the range covers all IP addresses starting with '192.168.4.' and ending with any value from '.0' to '.255'.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 6: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
The ACL 55 on R1 has four statements, in the following order, with address and wildcard mask values as follows:
1. 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255
2. 20.20.0.0 0.0.255.255
3. 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255
4. 2.2.2.0 0.0.0.255
If a router tried to match a packet sourced from IP address 20.20.20.20 using this ACL, which ACL statement does a router consider the packet to have matched?
Choices:
a. First statement
b. Second statement
c. Third statement
d. Forth statement
e. Implied deny at the end of the ACL
LLM Explanation: The router processes the ACL statements in order and stops at the first match. The IP address 20.20.20.20 matches the third statement (20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255) because the first 24 bits (20.20.20) match exactly and the last octet (20) falls within the wildcard mask range (0.0.0.255). The router considers this packet to have matched the third statement and will not process the subsequent statements or the implied deny.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'Cisco Documentation: IP Access List Processing - https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3 and a destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 28
b. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny tcp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 25 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is b. The access-list command 'access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25' matches the given criteria: - It denies packets with a UDP header (udp) - Allows any source IP address (any)  - Specifies a source port greater than 10455 (gt 10455) - Specifies a destination IP address of 30.3.3.3 (host 30.3.3.3) - Specifies a destination port equal to 25 (eq 25)  The other options are incorrect because: a. The destination port is 28 instead of 25 c. The protocol is TCP instead of UDP d. The source port is greater than 25 instead of 10455
URLs: ['Cisco Networking Academy - CCNA Routing and Switching: Routing and Switching Essentials v6.0', 'Cisco Documentation - Access Control Lists', 'Todd Lammle - CCNA Routing and Switching Complete Study Guide: Exam 100-105, Exam 200-105, Exam 200-125']

b. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 25 any eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.0.0.0 gt 10455 any eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25

This command specifies: protocol UDP, source IP 30.3.3.3, source port greater than 10455, any destination IP, and destination port equal to 25. The other options have incorrect IP addresses, port numbers, or syntax.

Question Text: Choose the wildcard mask that matches all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0, and mask 255.255.255.0.
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. To calculate the wildcard mask, subtract each octet of the subnet mask from 255. In this case, the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0, so the wildcard mask would be 0.0.0.255 (255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 0 = 255).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/26448-ACLsamples.html']

Question Text:
Given the following OSPF network commands,
type the wildcard masks to match the requirement.
Requirement: Match addresses that begin with 110.20
Command: network 110.20.0.0 {wildcard mask}
Which of the following wildcard mask will you use to meet the
requirement?
LLM Explanation: To match all addresses that begin with 110.20, the wildcard mask should be 0.0.255.255. This mask allows any value in the third and fourth octets, while fixing the first two octets to 110.20. The other options are incorrect because they either allow too much variation (like 0.255.255.255 which would match any address starting with 110) or are too restrictive (like 0.0.0.0 which would only match 110.20.0.0 exactly).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 20: OSPF Concepts and Configuration', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/13692-17.html']

Question Text: Which of the following network commands following the command router ospf 1, tells the router to start using OSPF on interfaces whose IP addresses are 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1?
LLM Explanation: The correct command is 'network 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255 area 0'. This command tells the router to start using OSPF on interfaces whose IP addresses match the network 20.0.0.0 with a wildcard mask of 0.255.255.255. The wildcard mask 0.255.255.255 matches any IP address that starts with 20, which includes 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 20: OSPF', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/7039-1.html']

Question Text: Given the following IP address - 20.54.23.3 and subnet mask - 255.255.255.0 choose the subnet ID and the broadcast address from that particular IP.
Choices:
a. Subnet ID: 20.54.23.0
Broadcast Address: 20.54.23.255
b. Subnet ID: 20.54.0.0
Broadcast Address: 20.54.0.255
c. Subnet ID: 20.54.0.0
Broadcast Address: 20.54.255.255
d. Subnet ID: 20.54.23.1
Broadcast Address: 20.54.23.255
LLM Explanation: The subnet ID is determined by performing a bitwise AND operation between the IP address and the subnet mask. In this case, 20.54.23.3 AND 255.255.255.0 results in 20.54.23.0, which is the subnet ID. The broadcast address is the last address in the subnet, obtained by setting all host bits to 1. With the given subnet mask, the host portion is the last octet, so the broadcast address is 20.54.23.255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'TCP/IP Guide: A Comprehensive, Illustrated Internet Protocols Reference, Charles M. Kozierok, No Starch Press, 2005']

LLM Explanation: The given binary mask 11111111.11111111.11000000.00000000 converts to the decimal notation 255.255.192.0. In this mask, the first two octets are all 1s, which convert to 255 in decimal. The third octet has the first two bits as 1s, which is 11000000 in binary, equivalent to 192 in decimal. The last octet is all 0s, which is simply 0 in decimal.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 13: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

LLM Explanation: The given binary mask 11111111.11100000.00000000.00000000 converted to decimal is 255.224.0.0. To convert each octet from binary to decimal, we calculate the sum of the bit values. In the second octet, 11100000 in binary equals 128 + 64 + 32 + 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 = 224 in decimal. The first octet is all 1's which equals 255, and the last two octets are all 0's which equal 0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 13: Subnet Design', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

LLM Explanation: The given binary mask is 11111110.00000000.00000000.00000000. Converting each octet to decimal:11111110 = 25400000000 = 000000000 = 0 00000000 = 0Therefore, the decimal representation of the subnet mask is 254.0.0.0, which corresponds to option b.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Your senior network engineer tells you to configure the DHCP server to lease the last 100 usable IP addresses in subnet 12.5.4.0/23. Which of the following IP addresses could be leased as a result of your new configuration?
LLM Explanation: In the subnet 12.5.4.0/23, the usable IP address range is 12.5.4.1 to 12.5.5.254. The last 100 usable IP addresses in this range would be 12.5.5.155 to 12.5.5.254. Of the given choices, only option c (12.5.4.254) falls within this range and could be leased by the DHCP server based on the specified configuration.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: IP Addressing', 'RFC 2131 - Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol']

Question Text:
You are working with a network engineer to design a network for the new Campus. He provided the following details:
The IP address is 195.240.37.43
The subnet mask is 255.255.255.224
You have been tasked to find the:
1. Network (N) bits
2. Subnet bits (S)
3. Host (H) bits.
Choices:
a. Network Bits = 15 | Subnet Bits = 2 | Host Bits = 1
b. Network Bits = 20 | Subnet Bits = 3 | Host Bits = 1
c. Network Bits = 24 | Subnet Bits = 3 | Host Bits = 5
d. Network Bits = 28 | Subnet Bits = 1 | Host Bits = 2
LLM Explanation: To determine the number of network, subnet, and host bits, we need to analyze the subnet mask. The subnet mask 255.255.255.224 in binary is 11111111.11111111.11111111.11100000. Counting the number of consecutive 1s from left to right, we get 27 bits. The first 24 bits represent the network portion, the next 3 bits (27-24) represent the subnet portion, and the remaining 5 bits (32-27) represent the host portion. Therefore, the correct answer is option c: Network Bits = 24, Subnet Bits = 3, and Host Bits = 5.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'Subnetting for Beginners: How to Easily Master IP Subnetting and Binary Math to Pass Your CCNA, Chase Andrews, 2018']

Question Text: Which of the following binary masks is equivalent to the 255.255.255.240 dotted-decimal notation (DDN)?
LLM Explanation: The binary mask 11111111.11111111.11111111.11110000 is equivalent to the dotted-decimal notation 255.255.255.240. In this mask, the first 28 bits are set to 1, and the last 4 bits are set to 0. This corresponds to a subnet mask with a prefix length of /28, meaning that the first 28 bits of the IP address are used for the network portion, and the remaining 4 bits are used for host addresses.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', "TCP/IP Guide by Charles M. Kozierok (Section 'IP Addressing and Subnetting')", 'Cisco Learning Network: IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users']

Question Text: Which of the following binary masks is equivalent to the 255.192.0.0 dotted-decimal notation (DDN)?
LLM Explanation: The binary mask 11111111.11000000.00000000.00000000 is equivalent to the dotted-decimal notation (DDN) 255.192.0.0. In this mask, the first 10 bits are set to 1, indicating the network portion of the address, while the remaining 22 bits are set to 0, representing the host portion. This corresponds to a /10 prefix length or subnet mask.

Question Text: Find the subnet ID from the IP address 10.75.20.3/24
LLM Explanation: The subnet ID is determined by performing a bitwise AND operation between the IP address and the subnet mask. In this case, with a /24 subnet mask (255.255.255.0), the subnet ID is obtained by setting all host bits to 0. This results in 10.75.20.0, which matches option c.

Question Text: Find the subnet ID from the IP address 10.75.20.4/17
LLM Explanation: To find the subnet ID, we need to perform a bitwise AND operation between the IP address and the subnet mask. A /17 subnet mask is 255.255.128.0 in dotted decimal notation. Performing the AND operation:10.75.20.4  = 00001010.01001011.00010100.00000100255.255.128.0 = 11111111.11111111.10000000.00000000--------------------------------------------------10.75.0.0    = 00001010.01001011.00000000.00000000The result is 10.75.0.0, which matches option b.

Question Text: Which of the following dotted-decimal notation (DDN) is equivalent of /17.
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask /17 in binary is 11111111.11111111.10000000.00000000, which converts to 255.255.128.0 in dotted decimal notation. Therefore, the correct answer is option d, 255.255.224.0.

Question Text: Which of the following dotted-decimal notation (DDN) is equivalent of /28.
LLM Explanation: The /28 subnet mask in binary is 11111111.11111111.11111111.11110000, which converts to 255.255.255.240 in dotted-decimal notation. This subnet mask has 28 network bits and 4 host bits, allowing for 14 usable host addresses per subnet.

Question Text: The broadcast address from the IP address 67.68.67.68/12 is 67.79.255.255.
LLM Explanation: The broadcast address from the IP address 67.68.67.68/12 is indeed 67.79.255.255. To determine this, we first identify the network and host portions of the address using the /12 subnet mask, which is 255.240.0.0 in dotted decimal notation. The first 12 bits (the network portion) of the IP address remain unchanged, while the remaining 20 bits (the host portion) are set to all 1s to create the broadcast address. In this case, 67.68.67.68 becomes 67.01000100.01000011.01000100 in binary. Keeping the first 12 bits unchanged and setting the remaining 20 bits to 1, we get 67.01001111.11111111.11111111, which translates to 67.79.255.255 in dotted decimal notation.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the prefix (CIDR) format equivalent of 255.255.254.0?
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.255.254.0 in binary is 11111111.11111111.11111110.00000000. Counting the number of consecutive 1s from the left gives us 23, which corresponds to the /23 prefix or CIDR notation.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the prefix (CIDR) format equivalent of 255.192.0.0?
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.192.0.0 is equivalent to the CIDR notation /10. To convert a subnet mask to CIDR notation, you count the number of consecutive 1 bits in the binary representation of the subnet mask. 255.192.0.0 in binary is 11111111.11000000.00000000.00000000, which has 10 consecutive 1 bits at the beginning. Therefore, the correct CIDR notation is /10.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Your task is to find the broadcast address from the IP address 10.75.20.3 with subnet mask 255.248.0.0
Choices:
a. Broadcast address: 10.75.255.255
b. Broadcast address: 10.75.20.255
c. Broadcast address: 10.79.255.255
d. Broadcast address: 10.80.255.255
LLM Explanation: To find the broadcast address, we need to determine the network and host portions of the IP address based on the subnet mask. The subnet mask 255.248.0.0 (/13) means that the first 13 bits are network bits, and the remaining 19 bits are host bits. In binary, 10.75.20.3 is 00001010.01001011.00010100.00000011. The first 13 bits (00001010.01001) represent the network portion, and the last 19 bits (011.00010100.00000011) represent the host portion. To get the broadcast address, we keep the network bits unchanged and set all host bits to 1. This gives us 00001010.01001111.11111111.11111111 in binary, which translates to 10.79.255.255 in decimal notation.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: IP Addressing)', 'Cisco Learning Network: https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/article/ip-addressing-and-subnetting-for-new-users']

Question Text: Your task is to find the broadcast address from the IP address 172.30.70.26 with subnet mask 255.255.192.0
Choices:
a. Broadcast address: 172.30.127.255
b. Broadcast address: 172.30.70.255
c. Broadcast address: 172.30.100.255
d. Broadcast address: 172.30.87.255
LLM Explanation: To find the broadcast address, we need to determine the network and host portions of the IP address using the subnet mask. The subnet mask 255.255.192.0 has 18 network bits (11111111.11111111.11000000.00000000), meaning the first 18 bits of the IP address represent the network, and the remaining 14 bits are for hosts. In binary, 172.30.70.26 is 10101100.00011110.01000110.00011010. The network portion is 10101100.00011110.01, and the host portion is 000110.00011010. To get the broadcast address, we set all host bits to 1, resulting in 10101100.00011110.01111111.11111111, which is 172.30.127.255 in decimal notation.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the dotted decimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /30?
LLM Explanation: The dotted decimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /30 is 255.255.255.252. A /30 subnet mask indicates that the first 30 bits are network bits, and the remaining 2 bits are host bits. When converted to DDN, this translates to 11111111.11111111.11111111.11111100 in binary, which is equivalent to 255.255.255.252.

Question Text: Which of the following answers lists the dotteddecimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /18?
LLM Explanation: The dotted-decimal notation (DDN) equivalent of /18 is 255.255.192.0. In CIDR notation, /18 means that the first 18 bits of the subnet mask are 1s, and the remaining 14 bits are 0s. When converted to DDN, this translates to 11111111.11111111.11000000.00000000, which is equivalent to 255.255.192.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following masks, when used within a Class B network, would supply enough subnet bits to support 90 subnets? (Choose two)
LLM Explanation: To support 90 subnets in a Class B network, 7 subnet bits are required (2^7 = 128 subnets). A /19 mask, represented as 255.255.224.0, borrows 3 bits from the host portion in the 3rd octet, providing 8 subnet bits in total (5 from the default Class B mask + 3 borrowed). This is sufficient for 90 subnets. The other masks either borrow too few bits (/21) or too many bits (/24 and 255.255.255.252), making them unsuitable.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 13: Analyzing Subnet Masks', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Your task is to troubleshoot a user’s PC with IP 10.20.30.5 and mask 255.255.255.0. Based on the given details type the number of the network (N), subnet (S), and host (H) bits.
Choices:
a. Network Bits = 16 | Subnet Bits = 15 | Host Bits = 1
b. Network Bits = 16 | Subnet Bits = 1 | Host Bits = 15
c. Network Bits = 8 | Subnet Bits = 8 | Host Bits = 16
d. Network Bits = 8 | Subnet Bits = 16 | Host Bits = 8
LLM Explanation: The IP address 10.20.30.5 with subnet mask 255.255.255.0 indicates that the first octet (10) represents the network portion, which is 8 bits. The subnet mask 255.255.255.0 has 24 bits set to 1, meaning that the subnet portion occupies the second and third octets (16 bits). The remaining 8 bits in the fourth octet are used for host addressing.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press', 'TCP/IP Guide: A Comprehensive, Illustrated Internet Protocols Reference, Charles M. Kozierok, No Starch Press']

LLM Explanation: To convert the binary mask to decimal, group the binary digits into octets and convert each octet to its decimal equivalent. The given binary mask is 11111111.11111111.11111110.00000000. Grouping into octets: 11111111 (255), 11111111 (255), 11111110 (254), 00000000 (0). Therefore, the decimal representation of the subnet mask is 255.255.254.0, which corresponds to choice b.

Question Text: Which of the following binary masks is equivalent to the 255.192.0.0 dotted-decimal notation (DDN)?
LLM Explanation: The dotted-decimal notation 255.192.0.0 is equivalent to the binary mask 11111111.11000000.00000000.00000000. In the second octet, 192 in decimal is 11000000 in binary, which matches option a. The other options have incorrect binary representations in the second octet.

Question Text:
The senior network engineer assigns you a task related to port security. He needs your help to configure the fa0/1 from the SW-examsD to accept frames only from the MAC 0200.1111.2222.
Type the commands that need to be configured on the SW-examsD following the requirements below:
1. configure the FastEthernet0/1 to be an access port
2. enable port security on that interface
3. define the allowed MAC address
Choices:
a. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/2
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security macaddress 0200.1111.2222
b. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/1
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
c. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/1
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security macaddress 0200.2222.2222
d. SW-examsD#configure terminal
SW-examsD(config)#interface FastEthernet0/1
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security
SW-examsD(config-if)#switchport port-security macaddress 0200.1111.2222
LLM Explanation: Option d is the correct set of commands to meet the given requirements. It configures FastEthernet0/1 as an access port, enables port security on that interface, and defines the allowed MAC address as 0200.1111.2222. Option a configures the wrong interface (fa0/2 instead of fa0/1). Option b enables port security but does not define the allowed MAC address. Option c defines the wrong allowed MAC address (0200.2222.2222 instead of 0200.1111.2222).
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 11: Implementing Ethernet Virtual LANs', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960/software/release/12-2_55_se/configuration/guide/scg_2960/swtrafc.html']

Question Text: One of Level 3's public DNS servers is ____________.
LLM Explanation: Level 3 Communications operates a public DNS server with the IP address 4.2.2.3. This is one of the well-known public DNS servers, along with Google's 8.8.8.8 and others. The other options are incorrect: 8.8.8.8 is Google's public DNS, 127.0.0.1 is the loopback address, and 192.168.1.1 is a common private IP address for home routers.

Question Text: Which of the following have examples of parallel composition? Select all that apply.
Choices:
a. Perform load balancing on any traffic that arrives from prefix 130.207.0.0/16 or is destined to port 80.
b. Perform MAC learning on all traffic that is not blocked by a firewall rule.
c. Count all port 80 traffic.
d. Block all traffic whose source IP address is contained in a list of blocked IP addresses.
e. Load balance traffic across multiple destination IP addresses and perform routing to the resulting destination IP addresses.
LLM Explanation: Parallel composition involves applying multiple policies or actions simultaneously to the same traffic. In choice a, load balancing is performed on traffic that matches either of two conditions (source prefix or destination port), which is an example of parallel composition. Similarly, in choice e, load balancing and routing are applied in parallel to the same traffic. The other choices describe sequential composition (b), a single action (c), or a conditional action (d), but not parallel composition.
URLs: ['https://sdn.systemsapproach.org/softwareflow.html#parallel-composition', 'https://www.usenix.org/system/files/conference/nsdi15/nsdi15-paper-jose.pdf']

Question Text: Which of the following is the appropriate Pyretic rule for matching traffic that sends packets from either 10.0.0.1 or 10.0.0.2 to IP address 1.2.3.4?
Choices:
a. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) + mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
b. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) + mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
c. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
d. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4))
e. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
LLM Explanation: The correct Pyretic rule for matching traffic from either source IP 10.0.0.1 or 10.0.0.2 to destination IP 1.2.3.4 is option c: (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4). The '+' operator allows matching either source IP, and the '>>' operator sequences this match with modifying the destination IP.
URLs: ['Pyretic: A Language and Runtime System for Network Virtualization and SDN Programming, NSDI 2013, https://www.usenix.org/system/files/conference/nsdi13/nsdi13-final126.pdf', 'Pyretic Github Repository Documentation, https://github.com/frenetic-lang/pyretic']

Question Text: Which of the following is the appropiate Pyretic rule for sending traffic from source IP address 10.0.0.1 to destination IP address 10.1.2.3 and traffic from source IP address 10.0.0.2 to destination IP address 10.2.3.4?
Choices:
a. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2)  + mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
b. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
c. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >>mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
d. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) + mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
e. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) & (match(srcip=10.0.0.2)  >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
LLM Explanation: The correct Pyretic rule for sending traffic from source IP 10.0.0.1 to destination IP 10.1.2.3 and traffic from source IP 10.0.0.2 to destination IP 10.2.3.4 is option b: (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4)). The '>>' operator in Pyretic represents sequential composition, meaning the first policy is applied followed by the second policy. The '+' operator represents parallel composition, allowing the two flow rules to be applied independently. The other options use incorrect operators or ordering of the policies.
URLs: ['Pyretic: A Language for Software Defined Networks - https://www.frenetic-lang.org/pyretic', 'Pyretic documentation - https://github.com/frenetic-lang/pyretic/wiki']

Question Text: What is the dotted notation of an IP address of 10000000 10000111 01000100 00000101? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: To convert a 32-bit binary IP address to dotted decimal notation, we divide it into four 8-bit segments (octets) and convert each octet to its decimal equivalent. The given IP address in binary is: 10000000 10000111 01000100 00000101. Converting each octet to decimal: - 10000000 = 128 - 10000111 = 135 - 01000100 = 68 - 00000101 = 5 Therefore, the correct dotted decimal notation of the given IP address is 128.135.68.5, which corresponds to choice b.
URLs: ['https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html', 'https://www.tutorialspoint.com/ipv4/ipv4_address_classes.htm']

Question Text: Given a network address 128.100.0.0, what is its network class type? Select one choice.
Choices:
a. Class A
b. Class B
c. Class C
d. None of the above
LLM Explanation: The network address 128.100.0.0 belongs to Class B. In IPv4 addressing, Class B networks have their first octet in the range 128 to 191. Since the first octet of the given address is 128, it falls under Class B.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: IP Addressing)', 'TCP/IP Illustrated, Volume 1: The Protocols by W. Richard Stevens (Chapter 2: The Internet Address Architecture)']

Question Text: What is the subnetwork number of a host with an IP address of 172.16.66.0/21? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: The subnetwork number of a host can be determined by performing a bitwise AND operation between the host IP address and the subnet mask. In this case, the subnet mask for a /21 network is 255.255.248.0. When 172.16.66.0 is ANDed with 255.255.248.0, the result is 172.16.64.0. This means that 172.16.66.0/21 belongs to the 172.16.64.0/21 subnetwork.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'TCP/IP Guide by Charles M. Kozierok (Chapter 16: IP Addressing Concepts and Issues)']

Question Text: What is the first valid host on the subnetwork that the node 172.30.190.198/24 belongs to? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: The first valid host on a /24 subnet is the network address plus one. With a /24 subnet mask (255.255.255.0), the host 172.30.190.198 belongs to the 172.30.190.0/24 subnet. The first valid host address on this subnet is 172.30.190.1, as the network address 172.30.190.0 cannot be assigned to a host.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: IP Addressing)', 'TCP/IP Guide by Charles M. Kozierok (Chapter 16: IPv4 Addressing)']

Question Text: Based on 1.1.1.0/24, the IP address would be: Select one choice.
Choices:
a. Class A
b. Class B
c. Class C
d. Class D
LLM Explanation: The IP address 1.1.1.0/24 belongs to Class C. In classful addressing, IP addresses are divided into classes based on the first octet value. Class A addresses have a first octet between 1-126, Class B between 128-191, and Class C between 192-223. Since the first octet of 1.1.1.0 is 1, it falls under the Class C range.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: IP Addressing)', "TCP/IP Guide by Charles M. Kozierok (Section 'IP Address Classes (Classful Addressing)')", 'Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach by James Kurose and Keith Ross (Chapter 4: The Network Layer)']

Question Text: Using CIDR notation, a prefix 205.100.0.0 of length 22 is written as 205.100.0.0/22. What network mask does the /22 notation indicate? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: In CIDR notation, the /22 indicates that the first 22 bits of the 32-bit IP address are the network prefix, while the remaining 10 bits are for host addresses. To determine the subnet mask, we convert the prefix length to binary. The first 22 bits are set to 1, and the remaining 10 bits are 0. This binary representation is 11111111.11111111.11111100.00000000, which corresponds to the dotted decimal subnet mask 255.255.252.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Perform CIDR aggregation on the following /24 IP addresses: 128.58.24.0/24, 128.58.25.0/24, 128.58.26.0/24, 128.58.27.0/24. What is the CIDR outcome? Select one choice.
LLM Explanation: To perform CIDR aggregation, we need to find the common network prefix among the given IP addresses. In this case, the first three octets (128.58) are the same for all addresses, and the fourth octet values are contiguous (24, 25, 26, 27). By borrowing 2 bits from the fourth octet, we can aggregate these four /24 networks into a single /22 network. The network address for the aggregated network is determined by setting the borrowed bits to 0, resulting in 128.58.24.0/22.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: IP Addressing)', 'Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach by James Kurose and Keith Ross (Chapter 4: The Network Layer)']

Question Text: Please select all of the valid IP addresses. Check all that apply.
LLM Explanation: The valid IP addresses are 192.168.1.1 and 8.8.8.8. An IP address consists of four numbers, each ranging from 0 to 255, separated by dots. 257.70.312.49 is invalid because the first number exceeds 255. 123.456.123.456 is also invalid as each number cannot exceed 255.

Question Text: Which of the following is a correct form of CIDR notation?
LLM Explanation: CIDR notation is a compact representation of an IP address and its associated network mask. The correct format is an IP address, followed by a forward slash, and then the number of network bits. In this case, 192.168.1.0/24 correctly denotes the IP address 192.168.1.0 with a 24-bit network mask, which is equivalent to the subnet mask 255.255.255.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: IP Addressing)', 'Wikipedia: Classless Inter-Domain Routing (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classless_Inter-Domain_Routing)']

Question Text: Consider the following scenario: Your IP address is 192.168.8.34, and your subnet mask is 255.255.0.0. What part of the subnet mask represents the subnet ID?
Choices:
a. 255.255.0.1
b. The last two octets of the subnet mask, 0.0
c. The first two octets of the subnet mask, 255.255
d. 192.168.0.254
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.255.0.0 is used to determine which part of the IP address represents the network ID and which part represents the host ID. The first two octets (255.255) of the subnet mask represent the subnet ID, while the last two octets (0.0) represent the host ID. Therefore, the correct answer is that the first two octets of the subnet mask, 255.255, represent the subnet ID.
URLs: ['Lammle, T. (2018). CompTIA Network+ Study Guide: Exam N10-007 (4th ed.). John Wiley & Sons.', 'Odom, W. (2020). CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1. Cisco Press.']

Question Text: Which of the following are non-routable IP addresses? (Select all that apply)
LLM Explanation: The IP address ranges 172.16.0.0/12, 10.0.0.0/8, and 192.168.0.0/16 are all non-routable IP addresses. These are private IP address ranges reserved for use within private networks and cannot be routed on the public Internet. 9.0.0.0 is a public IP address.
URLs: ['IETF RFC 1918: Address Allocation for Private Internets', 'IANA IPv4 Special-Purpose Address Registry']

Question Text: A Layer 2 switch configuration places all its physical ports into VLAN 2. The IP addressing plan shows that address 175.28.1.150 (with mask 255.255.255.0) is reserved for use by this new LAN switch and that 175.28.1.254 is already configured on the router connected to that same VLAN. The switch needs to support SSH connections into the switch from any subnet in the network. Which of the following commands are part of the required configuration in this case? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. The switch cannot support SSH because all its ports connect to VLAN 2, and the IP address must be configured on interface VLAN 1.
b. The ip address 175.28.1.150 255.255.255.0 command in interface vlan 2 configuration mode.
c. The ip default-gateway 175.28.1.254 command in global configuration mode.
d. The ip address 172.16.2.250 255.255.255.0 command in interface vlan 1 configuration mode.
e. The ip default-gateway 175.28.1.150 command in global configuration mode.
LLM Explanation: To configure the Layer 2 switch with the given IP address and enable SSH access, the switch needs an IP address on the VLAN interface corresponding to the VLAN where all ports are assigned (VLAN 2 in this case). This is done with the 'ip address 175.28.1.150 255.255.255.0' command in interface vlan 2 configuration mode. Additionally, the switch needs a default gateway configured to reach other subnets, which is set with the 'ip default-gateway 175.28.1.254' command in global configuration mode, using the router's IP address in that VLAN.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 8: Configuring Basic Switch Management', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960/software/release/15-2_2_e/configuration/guide/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg_chapter_0100.html']

Question Text:
You have been tasked to configure the IPv4 address on the switch only on the VLAN 1 following the details below.
Configuration details:
IP address: 199.255.240.100
Subnet mask: 255.255.255.0
Default gateway: 199.255.240.1
Which of the following commands will you type to complete the task?
Choices:
a. Examsdigest#(config)# interface vlan 1
Examsdigest#(config-line)# ip address 199.255.240.100 255.255.255.0
Examsdigest#(config-line)# no shutdown
Examsdigest#(config-line)# end
Examsdigest#(config)# ip default-gateway 199.255.240.1
b. Examsdigest#(config)# interface vlan 1
Examsdigest#(config-line)# ip address 199.255.241.100 255.255.255.0
Examsdigest#(config-line)# no shutdown
Examsdigest#(config-line)# end
Examsdigest#(config)# ip default-gateway 199.255.240.1
c. Examsdigest#(config)# interface vlan 1
Examsdigest#(config-line)# ip address 199.255.240.100 255.255.0.0
Examsdigest#(config-line)# no shutdown
Examsdigest#(config-line)# end
Examsdigest#(config)# ip default-gateway 199.255.240.1
d. Examsdigest#(config)# interface vlan 11
Examsdigest#(config-line)# ip address 199.255.240.100 255.255.255.0
Examsdigest#(config-line)# no shutdown
Examsdigest#(config-line)# end
Examsdigest#(config)# ip default-gateway 199.255.240.1
LLM Explanation: Option 'a' provides the correct commands to configure the IPv4 address on the switch for VLAN 1 based on the given configuration details. It enters the VLAN 1 interface configuration mode, sets the correct IP address and subnet mask, enables the interface with 'no shutdown', exits back to global configuration mode, and sets the correct default gateway.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 11: Implementing Ethernet Virtual LANs', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960/software/release/15-2_2_e/configuration/guide/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg_chapter_0101.html']

Question Text:
Which of the following command will you type to produce the output below?
"Vlan1 is up, line protocol is up
Hardware is EtherSVI, address is 0023.e21b.4cc0 (bia 0023.e21b.4cc0)
Internet address is 192.168.1.101/24
MTU 1500 bytes, BW 1000000 Kbit, DLY 10 usec, reliability 255/255, txload 1/255, rxload 1/255"
Choices:
a. show interfaces vlans
b. show interfaces
c. show interfaces vlan 1
d. show vlan 1
LLM Explanation: The command 'show interfaces vlan 1' is the correct choice to produce the given output. This command displays detailed information about the specified VLAN interface, including its status, hardware type, MAC address, IP address, MTU, bandwidth, delay, reliability, and load. The other options are either incorrect or do not exist as valid Cisco IOS commands.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/interface/command/ir-cr-book/ir-s4.html#wp3592423220', 'Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom']

Question Text: Which of the following addresses are not valid Class A network IDs? (Choose all that apply)
LLM Explanation: Class A network IDs range from 1.0.0.0 to 126.0.0.0. The addresses 140.0.0.0, 127.0.0.0, and 195.0.0.0 are not valid Class A network IDs because: - 140.0.0.0 falls within the Class B IP address range (128.0.0.0 to 191.255.0.0)   - 127.0.0.0 is reserved for loopback addresses and cannot be used as a network ID - 195.0.0.0 falls within the Class C IP address range (192.0.0.0 to 223.255.255.0)
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 13: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'RFC 791 - Internet Protocol, Information Sciences Institute, University of Southern California, September 1981']

Question Text: Which of the following addresses are valid Class C network IDs? (Choose two answers)
LLM Explanation: Class C network IDs have the first three octets representing the network portion, and the last octet representing the host portion. The first octet of a Class C network ID must be between 192 and 223 inclusive. Both 195.0.0.0 and 222.0.0.0 meet these criteria, making them valid Class C network IDs. 22.22.3.0 is a Class A address, 191.255.255.0 is an invalid network ID due to the host portion being all ones, and 127.0.0.0 is reserved for loopback addresses.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 13: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'TCP/IP Illustrated, Volume 1: The Protocols, Kevin R. Fall, W. Richard Stevens, Chapter 2: Link Layer']

Question Text: Which of the following IPv4 addresses has a subnet mask 255.255.0.0?
LLM Explanation: The IP address 10.0.0.56 belongs to the Class A private address range 10.0.0.0 to 10.255.255.255. Class A networks use a default subnet mask of 255.0.0.0, which can be further subnetted. In this case, the subnet mask 255.255.0.0 is a valid subnet mask for the 10.0.0.0 network, allowing for 65,536 subnets each with 65,534 usable host addresses.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'RFC 1918: Address Allocation for Private Internets']

Question Text: Which of the following IPv4 addresses has a subnet mask 255.255.255.0?
LLM Explanation: The IP address 10.0.0.56 belongs to the private IP address range 10.0.0.0/8, which uses a default subnet mask of 255.0.0.0. However, the question specifies a subnet mask of 255.255.255.0, which is commonly used for smaller subnets within the private IP ranges. This subnet mask is compatible with the 10.0.0.56 address, as it allows for 254 usable host addresses in the 10.0.0.0/24 subnet. The other IP addresses given (a, b, and c) are public IP addresses and do not typically use the 255.255.255.0 subnet mask.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'RFC 1918: Address Allocation for Private Internets']

Question Text: Which of the following IPv4 addresses has a subnet mask 255.0.0.0? (Choose all that apply)
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.0.0.0 corresponds to a /8 network prefix, meaning the first octet of the IP address represents the network portion. Among the given choices, only 10.0.0.56 belongs to a /8 network, as 10.0.0.0/8 is one of the private IP address ranges defined in RFC 1918. The other IP addresses have different network prefixes and thus do not have a 255.0.0.0 subnet mask.
URLs: ['RFC 1918 - Address Allocation for Private Internets (https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1918)', 'Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: IP Addressing (https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-volume-1-9780135792735)']

Question Text: Which of the following ranges is a valid class B network numbers?
LLM Explanation: Class B network numbers range from 128.0.0.0 to 191.255.255.255. The first octet of Class B networks is between 128 and 191, and the default subnet mask is 255.255.0.0. Choice 'a' correctly represents this range, while the other choices are invalid or represent different classes of IP addresses.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following ranges is a valid class C network numbers?
LLM Explanation: Class C network numbers range from 192.0.0.0 to 223.255.255.0. This range allows for 2,097,152 Class C networks, each supporting up to 254 hosts. Class A ranges from 1.0.0.0 to 126.0.0.0 (choice b), Class B from 128.0.0.0 to 191.255.0.0 (choice a), and Class D, used for multicast, from 224.0.0.0 to 239.255.255.255 (partially overlapping with choice d).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 13: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'RFC 791 - Internet Protocol', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following is the default mask of the IP 10.2.0.0?
LLM Explanation: The IP address 10.2.0.0 belongs to the Class A address range, which has a default subnet mask of 255.0.0.0. Class A addresses use the first octet for the network portion and the remaining three octets for the host portion. Therefore, the default subnet mask for Class A addresses is 255.0.0.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', "TCP/IP Guide by Charles M. Kozierok, Section 'IP Address Class A, B and C Network and Host Capacities'"]

Question Text: What information can you extract having the IP address 172.16.99.45? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. The network ID is 172.0.0.0.
b. The default mask for the network is 255.255.255.0.
c. The network is a Class B network.
d. The number of host bits in the unsubnetted network is 16.
e. The broadcast address of the network is 172.255.255.255
LLM Explanation: The IP address 172.16.99.45 belongs to the Class B private address range (172.16.0.0 to 172.31.255.255). Class B networks have a default subnet mask of 255.255.0.0, which means that the first two octets (16 bits) represent the network portion, and the last two octets (16 bits) represent the host portion of the address. Therefore, the network is a Class B network, and the number of host bits in the unsubnetted network is 16.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'RFC 1918: Address Allocation for Private Internets']

Question Text:
The senior network engineer asked you to choose the broadcast address from the last subnet according to the following details:
Network 172.28.0.0 (Class B)
Mask 255.255.0.0 (for all subnets)
LLM Explanation: The correct broadcast address for the last subnet in the 172.28.0.0/16 network is 172.28.255.255. To determine this, we first identify that it's a Class B network with the default mask of 255.255.0.0 (/16). This means there are 16 network bits and 16 host bits. The broadcast address for each subnet is the last address in that subnet, where all host bits are set to 1. Since the question asks for the last subnet, that means all subnet bits will also be set to 1, resulting in 172.28.255.255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text:
The senior network engineer asked you to choose the last usable address for a host from the last subnet according to the following details:
Network 9.0.0.0 (Class A)
Mask 255.255.0.0 (for all subnets)
LLM Explanation: The network 9.0.0.0 with a subnet mask of 255.255.0.0 is a Class A network that has been subnetted. The mask 255.255.0.0 provides 16 bits for the network portion and 16 bits for the host portion. This means there are 2^16 - 2 = 65,534 usable host addresses per subnet. The last subnet in this network would have the network address 9.255.0.0, and the last usable host address in that subnet would be 9.255.255.254, one less than the broadcast address of 9.255.255.255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom', 'TCP/IP Guide by Charles M. Kozierok', 'Internetworking with TCP/IP Vol.1: Principles, Protocols, and Architecture by Douglas Comer']

Question Text:
Examine the following show command output on a router configured for dynamic NAT:
"— Inside Source
access-list 1 pool examsdigest
pool examsdigest: netmask 255.255.255.240
start 190.1.1.1 end 190.1.1.10
type generic, total addresses 10, allocated 10 (100%), misses 595"
You are responsible to find out why users are not being able to reach the Internet.
Choices:
a. The cause is not related to dynamic NAT
b. The command output does not provide any clue to identify the problem
c. Dynamic NAT can't use Standard ACLs
d. The NAT pool does not have enough entries to fulfill the user's requests
LLM Explanation: The output shows that the NAT pool 'examsdigest' has a total of 10 addresses available, and all 10 are currently allocated (100% allocated). Additionally, there have been 595 'misses', meaning there were 595 attempts to allocate an address from the pool when no addresses were available. This indicates that the NAT pool is exhausted and does not have enough entries to fulfill all the user requests, preventing some users from accessing the Internet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 10: Network Address Translation', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/13772-12.html']

Question Text: R1 and R2 are attached to the same Ethernet VLAN, with subnet 192.168.1.0/24, and addresses 192.168.1.1, 192.168.2 respectively. The routers use an FHRP. Host A and host B attach to the same LAN and have correct default router settings per the FHRP configuration. Which of the following statements is true for this LAN?
Choices:
a. You can't connect two routers to the same LAN subnet.
b. If one router fails, hosts can't send packets off-subnet
c. If one router fails, both hosts will use the one remaining router as a default router
d. if one router fails, only one of the two hosts will still be able to send packets off-subnet
LLM Explanation: When two routers are connected to the same LAN subnet and configured with a First Hop Redundancy Protocol (FHRP) like HSRP or VRRP, they provide redundancy for the default gateway. If one router fails, the other router will take over as the active router for the FHRP group. In this scenario, both hosts A and B have their default gateway set to the virtual IP address of the FHRP group. So if one router fails, both hosts will automatically start using the remaining router as their default gateway, allowing them to continue sending packets off-subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: First Hop Redundancy Protocol', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/hot-standby-router-protocol-hsrp/9234-hsrpguidetoc.html']
